ms|work=[[The Guardian]]|quote=\"Currently, most R&D investment is concentrated in the south-east, London and the east, with the \u201cgolden triangle\u201d universities of Oxford, Cambridge, University College London, Imperial College and the LSE taking over a quarter of the pot.}}</ref>\n|30em}}\n\n{{University associations and groupings in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{University of Cambridge}}\n{{University of Oxford}}\n{{Imperial College London}}\n{{London School of Economics}}\n{{University College London|affiliates}}\n{{King's College London}}\n{{Science and technology in the United Kingdom}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Colloquial terms for groups of universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Innovation in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Universities in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Golden Triangle (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Location map+|United Kingdom|AlternativeMap=United_Kingdom_relief_location_map.jpg|alt=Map of the UK with location of 'golden triangle' universities highlighted|caption=Locations of 'golden triangle' universities.|float=right|width=388|places=\n{{Location map~|United Kingdom|lat=51.76|long=-1.25|position=left|label=[[University of Oxford|Oxford]]}}\n{{Location map~|United Kingdom|lat=52.21|long=0.12|position=right|label=[[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]]}}\n{{Location map~|United Kingdom|lat=51.51|long=-0.13|position=right|label='''London'''|mark=City locator 11.svg|marksize=12}}\n\n<!--LONDON UNIVERSITIES IN BOTTOM LEFT CORNER-->\n{{Location map~|United Kingdom|mark=TransparentPlaceholder.png|marksize=1|lat=51|long=-11\n|label='''London:'''<br/>\n&nbsp;[[Imperial College London|Imperial&nbsp;College&nbsp;London]]<br/>\n&nbsp;[[King's College London|King's&nbsp;College&nbsp;London]]<br/>\n&nbsp;[[London School of Economics|London&nbsp;School&nbsp;of&nbsp;Economics]]<br/>\n&nbsp;[[University College London|University&nbsp;College&nbsp;London]]\n|position=right}}\n}}\nThe '''golden triangle''' is an unofficial grouping of research universities located in the cities of [[Cambridge]], [[London]] and [[Oxford]] in the southeast of England.{{refn|group=note|Multiple sources state the golden triangle is formed around Oxford, Cambridge and London<ref name=THE95/><ref name=Indy12/><ref name=FT15/><ref name=ReLocate15/><ref name=NewScientist05/><ref name=TES15/>}} The triangle is occasionally referred to as the '''Loxbridge''' triangle,<ref>{{cite web|first=Michael |last=Neuman|year=2018|url=http://talks.cam.ac.uk/talk/index/98671|website=talks.cam.ac.uk|title=The Loxbridge Triangle: Integrating the East-West Arch into the London Mega-region|publisher=University of Cambridge}}</ref><ref name=loxbridge>{{cite journal | author=Morgan, K. J. | title= The research assessment exercise in English universities, 2001 | journal=Higher Education | volume=48 | pages=461&ndash;482 | year=2004 | doi= 10.1023/B:HIGH.0000046717.11717.06 | issue=4|jstor= 4151567}}</ref> a [[portmanteau]] of London and [[Oxbridge]].\n\nThe corners of the triangle are formed by the [[University of Cambridge]], the [[University of Oxford]] and various universities in [[London]]. These are typically [[Imperial College London]], [[University College London]], [[King's College London]] and the [[London School of Economics]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Social Class in the 21st Century|author=Mike Savage|date= 5 November 2015|publisher=Penguin|quote=\"Higher education researchers often talk about a 'Golden Triangle' of universities. The 'triangle' describes an imaginary three-sided shape with corners in Oxford, Cambridge and London. The exact composition of the London 'corner' can vary, but typically it includes the London School of Economics, King's College London, University College London and Imperial College London.\"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TE3ZCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT167#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=167|isbn=9780141978925}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|Multiple sources confirm the membership, although some omit either King's or LSE, as noted under their entries<ref name=Nature05/><ref name=THE09/><ref name=THE10/><ref name=BBC13/><ref name=RF14/><ref name=Guardian03/><ref name=OECD08/><ref name=Grant05/><ref name=THE02/><ref name=Guardian2017/>}} although some sources omit either or both of King's College London{{refn|group=note|King's College London is not included by<ref name=loxbridge/><ref name=THE09/><ref name=THE10/><ref name=Guardian03/><ref name=OECD08/><ref name=THE02/><ref name=Guardian2017/>}} and the London School of Economics.{{refn|group=note|LSE is not included by<ref name=Nature05/><ref name=Guardian03/><ref name=OECD08/><ref name=THE02/>}} Occasionally other universities in London will also be included, such as the [[London Business School]] and the [[London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/world-reputation-rankings-2014-results/2011860.article|title= World Reputation Rankings 2014 results: UK's 'golden triangle' accounts for 8 of the country's 10 representatives in top 100|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\nGolden triangle universities possess some of the largest UK university [[financial endowment]]s; endowment sizes range from UCL's \u00a3139&nbsp;million (2019)<ref name=\"UCL1819\"/> to Cambridge's \u00a36.44&nbsp;billion (including colleges)<ref name=\"Cambridge Endowment\"/> Further, each university receives millions of pounds in research fundings and other grants from the UK government, criticised by leaders of some other universities as disproportionate and not in the best interests of the country as a whole.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/south-secures-research-cash/207821.article|title=South secures research cash|date=16 February 2007|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|author=Rebecca Attwood}}</ref> In 2013/14, universities in Oxford, Cambridge and London received 46% of research funding in the UK, up from 42.6% a decade earlier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediafhe.com/golden-triangle-increases-share-of-research-funding |title=Golden triangle increases share of research funding}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellspacing=4 style=\"text-align:left; margin-right:0;\" class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Institution\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Location\n!Undergraduate enrollment ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\">{{HESA citation}}</ref>\n!Graduate enrollment ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n!Total enrollment ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n!2019 Endowment\n!Academic staff (2018/19)<ref name=AcStaff>{{cite web|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/staff/working-in-he#provider|publisher=[[Higher Education Statistics Agency]] |title=Who's working in HE |accessdate=3 March 2020|at=Staff numbers by HE provider }}</ref>\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Motto\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Colours\n|-\n|[[University of Cambridge]]\n|Cambridge,<br>[[Cambridgeshire]]\n|{{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0114}} \n|{{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0114}} \n|{{HESA student population|INSTID=0114}} \n|[[Pounds sterling|\u00a3]]6.441&nbsp;billion (including colleges){{small| ({{as of|2018|July|31|lc=y}})}}\n{{refn|Colleges \u00a33,188.2M,<ref name=\"Cambridge Endowment\">{{cite web|url=http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/reporter/2018-19/weekly/6530/Notes-to-Accounts-2018.pdf|title=Accounts of the Colleges 2017-18|author=|date=|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> University (consolidated) \u00a33,253.0M<ref name=CamUni2018>{{cite web|url=https://www.cam.ac.uk/system/files/uoc_annual_report_2018.pdf|title=REPORTS AND FINANCIAL STATEMENT 2018|publisher=University of Cambridge |accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>}}\n|6,215\n|''Hinc lucem et pocula sacra''<br />(From this place, we gain enlightenment and precious knowledge) \n|{{scarf|{{cell|#A3C1AD}}}}Cambridge Blue<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/offices/comm