19 />\n|1,725\n|''Rerum cognoscere causas''<br />(To Know the Causes of Things)\n|{{scarf|{{cell2|#800080}}{{cell|#000}}{{cell|#FFD700}}{{cell|#000}}{{cell2|#800080}}{{cell|#000}}{{cell|#FFD700}}{{cell|#000}}{{cell2|#800080}}}}Purple, black and gold<ref>{{cite web |url=https://lseshop.com/collections/clothing/products/woollen-scraf-with-crest-embroidery |title=LSE Shop |publisher=lseshop.com |accessdate=29 April 2019 }}</ref> \n|- \n|[[University of Oxford]]\n|Oxford,<br>[[Oxfordshire]]\n|{{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0156}}\n| {{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0156}}  \n| {{HESA student population|INSTID=0156}} \n|[[\u00a3]]6.1&nbsp;billion (including colleges) {{small|(as of 31 July 2018)}}{{refn|Colleges \u00a34.896 billion,<ref name=OxColl2018>{{cite web|url=http://d307gmaoxpdmsg.cloudfront.net/collegeaccounts1718/aggregated.pdf|title=Oxford University Colleges Financial Statements 2018|publisher=University of Oxford|access-date=16 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411222529/http://d307gmaoxpdmsg.cloudfront.net/collegeaccounts1718/aggregated.pdf|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> University (consolidated) \u00a31.161&nbsp;billion<ref name=OxUni2018>{{cite web|url=https://www.ox.ac.uk/sites/files/oxford/field/field_document/University%20of%20Oxford%2C%20Financial%20Statements%202017-2018.pdf|title=Financial Statements 2017/18|publisher=University of Oxford|access-date=16 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223034837/https://www.ox.ac.uk/sites/files/oxford/field/field_document/University%20of%20Oxford%2C%20Financial%20Statements%202017-2018.pdf|archive-date=23 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n|6,905\n|''Dominus Illuminatio Mea''<br />(The Lord is my Light)\n|{{scarf|{{cell|#002147}}}} Oxford blue<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/branding_toolkit/the_brand_colours/ |title=The brand colour \u2013 Oxford blue |publisher=University of Oxford |accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[University College London]]\n|London,<br>[[Greater London]]\n|{{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0149}} \n|{{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0149}} \n|{{HESA student population|INSTID=0149}} \n|[[pound sterling|\u00a3]]138.7&nbsp;million<ref name=UCL1819 />\n|7,700\n|''Cuncti adsint meritaeque expectent praemia palmae''<br/>(Let all come who by merit deserve the most reward)\n|{{scarf|{{cells|3|#602899}}{{cell|#6cf}}{{cells|3|#602899}}{{cell|#6cf}}{{cells|3|#602899}}}}\n|}\n\n==Rankings==\n\n===World===\n{{See also|College and university rankings}}\n\nGolden triangle universities generally do well on International rankings, which strongly reflect research performance. The LSE has, however, expressed concerns about a bias in rankings against smaller institutions and in favour of universities with large science, technology, engineering and mathematics programmes. Some global rankings, such as those produced by [[Times Higher Education World University Rankings|Times Higher Education]] (THE) and [[QS World University Rankings|Quacquarelli Symonds]] (QS), correct for the sizes of institutions in calculating their results but others, such as the [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]] (ARWU), make no such adjustment.<ref name=\"LSE rankings\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hepi.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Hepi_International-university-rankings-For-good-or-for-ill-REPORT-89-10_12_16_Screen.pdf|title=International university rankings: For good or ill?|author=Bahram Bekhradnia |publisher=Higher Education Policy Institute|date=15 December 2016|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! University\n! ''[[Times Higher Education World University Rankings|THE World]]'' (2020)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2020/world-ranking|title=World University Rankings 2020|last=|first=|work=Times Higher Education (THE)}}</ref>\n! ''[[QS World University Rankings|QS World]]'' (2020)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2020|title=QS World University Rankings 2020|last=|first=|work=Top Universities}}</ref>\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | ''[[U.S. News & World Report Best Global University Ranking|US News Global]]'' (2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-global-universities/rankings|title=Best Global Universities Rankings|last=|first=|date=|work=US News and World Report|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028092904/http://www.usnews.com/education/best-global-universities/rankings|archive-date=2014-10-28}}</ref>\n! ''THE Global Employability'' (2019)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/student/best-universities/graduate-employability-top-universities-uk-ranked-employers|title=Graduate employability: top universities in the UK ranked by employers|last=|first=|work=Times Higher Education (THE)}}</ref>\n!''Academic Ranking of World Universities'' (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/ARWU2019.html|title=ARWU World University Rankings 2019 {{!}} Academic Ranking of World Universities 2019 {{!}} Top 1000 universities {{!}} Shanghai Ranking - 2019|website=www.shanghairanking.com|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[University of Cambridge]]\n|3\n|7\n|9\n|4\n|3\n|-\n| [[Imperial College London]]\n|10\n|9\n|20\n|26\n|23\n|-\n| [[King's College London]]\n|36\n|33\n|37\n|31\n|51\n|-\n| [[London School of Economics]]{{refn |group=note|The LSE made the following statement about university rankings in 2012: \"At mid-2012, LSE has seen pleasing improvements over the last couple of years in our standing in all the main global rankings: those produced by Times Higher Education, QS and Shanghai Jiaotong University. We have also seen good rises in the domestic UK rankings. But we remain concerned that all of the global rankings \u2013 by some way the most important for us, given our highly international orientation \u2013 suffer from inbuilt biases in favour of large multi-faculty universities with full STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics) offerings, and against small, specialist, mainly non-STEM universities such as LSE.\"<ref name=\"LSE rankings\">{{cite web|title=LSE in university league tables|url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/aboutLSE/leagueTables/LSEinUniversityLeagueTables.aspx|publisher=London School of Economics|archivedate=4 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055639/http://www.lse.ac.uk/aboutLSE/leagueTables/LSEinUniversityLeagueTables.aspx}}</ref>}}\n|27\n|44\n|259\n|72\n|151-200\n|-\n| [[University of Oxford]]\n|1\n|4\n|5\n|11\n|7\n|-\n| [[University College London]]\n|15\n|8\n|21\n|105\n|15\n|}\n\n===National===\n{{See also|Rankings of universities in the United Kingdom}}\n\nThe Golden Triangle universities generally do well on British university league tables, with Cambridge and Oxford consistently first and second, and Imperial and UCL ranked in the top ten by all compilers. The LSE, however, misses out on a top ten place in the [[The Guardian|Guardian University Guide]], while\nKing's College London fails to make the top ten except in the [[Times Higher Education]] employability survey of UK recruiters.\n\nIn ''The Sunday Times''' 10-year (1998\u20132007) average ranking of British universities based on consistent league table performance; Cambridge, Oxford, LSE, Imperial and UCL (in order) claimed the top 5 positions whilst King's was placed joint 14th.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://extras.timesonline.co.uk/pdfs/univ07ten.pdf|title=University ranking based on performance over 10 years|work=The Times |location=London |year=2007|accessdate=28 April 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080414064446/http://extras.timesonline.co.uk/pdfs/univ07ten.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 14 April 2008}}</ref> With the exception of King's, the remaining members of the Golden Triangle have never left the top 15 in one of the three main domestic rankings between 2008 and 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Domestic Ranking of British Universisities over a 10-Year Period|url=http://theuniversitybuzz.blogspot.co.uk/2017/01/domestic-ranking-of-british.html|publisher=The University Buzz}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! University\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | ''[[Rankings of universities in the United Kingdom#THE Table of Tables|THE Table of Tables]]'' (2020)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/table-tables-2020-bath-joins-top-10|title=THE 'Table of Tables' 2020: Bath joins top 10|first=|work=Times Higher Education|access-date=}}</ref>\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | ''[[Rankings of universities in the United Kingdom#The Complete University Guide|Complete]]'' (2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings|title=University League Tables 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Complete University Guide}}</ref>\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | ''[[Times Higher Education|THE UK Employability]]'' (2019)<ref name=\":0\" />\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | ''[[Rankings of universities in the United Kingdom#The Guardian|Guardian]]'' (2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/ng-interactive/2019/jun/07/university-league-tables-2020|title=University league tables 2020|last=|first=|date=7 June 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=}}</ref>\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | ''[[Rankings of universities in the United Kingdom#The Times and Sunday Times|The Times]]'' (2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/good-university-guide-in-full-tp6dzs7wn|title=The Times and Sunday Times University Good University Guide 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=}}{{paywall}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[University of Cambridge]]\n| 1\n| 1\n| 1\n| 1\n| 1\n|-\n| [[Imperial College London]]\n| 4\n| 5\n|3\n| 7\n| 4\n|-\n| [[King's College London]]\n| N/A\n| 25\n|4\n| 63\n| 28\n|-\n| [[London School of Economics]]\n| 9\n| 4\n|6\n| 19\n| 11\n|-\n| [[University of Oxford]]\n| 2\n| 2\n| 2\n| 3\n| 2\n|-\n| [[University College London]]\n| 13\n| 10\n|8\n| 22\n| 7\n|}\n\n==Research income==\nThe institutions typically considered members of the triangle have among the highest research incomes of all British universities and collaborate closely through initiatives such as the [[G5 (universities)|G5]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=186508&sectioncode=26|title=Super elite in secret bid for cash boost|work=Times Higher Education|date=6 February 2004|accessdate=30 March 2014}}</ref> [[Global Medical Excellence Cluster|Global Medical Cluster (GMEC)]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmecuk.com/members/universities|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306214506/http://www.gmecuk.com/members/universities|archivedate=6 March 2014|accessdate=4 August 2016|title=Universities|website=GMEC}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2006/dec/19/research.highereducation \"Collaborate and listen, The Guardian, Tuesday 19 December 2006\"]</ref> [[MedCity (London)|MedCity]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-26938737|title=MedCity launched to promote South East's science 'golden triangle'|accessdate=8 April 2014|work=BBC News|date=8 April 2014}}</ref> and [[SES (universities)|SES]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/research-heavyweights-deny-ganging-up/2003702.article|title=Research heavyweights deny 'ganging up'|work=Times Higher Education|date=9 May 2013|accessdate=30 March 2014}}</ref> The balance of funding between the 'golden triangle' and the rest of the UK has been questioned, and was specifically included in the terms of reference for an enquiry in 2018 by the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] [[Science and Technology Select Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/science-and-technology-committee/news-parliament-2017/research-innovation-spending-inquiry-launch-17-19/|title= Balance and effectiveness of research and innovation spending inquiry launched|at=Terms of Reference|date=20 July 2018|accessdate=13 December 2018|publisher=House of Commons}}</ref> According to defenders of the level of funding going to the golden triangle institutions, \"The apparent concentration of research in the golden triangle is little more than a reflection of the distribution of people in the UK\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/opinion/cuts-golden-triangle-could-leave-uk-bad-shape|title= Cuts to the golden triangle could leave the UK in bad shape|date=6 December 2018|work=Times Higher Education|author=Sarah Chaytor and Graeme Reid}}</ref> Analysis of grant proposals to [[Research Councils UK]] between 2012\u201313 and 2016\u201317 has shown that golden triangle institutions do not have unusually high success rates (two are actually below the expected range), but that the northern universities of [[Durham University|Durham]], [[Lancaster University|Lancaster]] and [[University of York|York]] do.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.esrc.ac.uk/2018/09/27/putting-research-in-its-place/|title=Putting research in its place|date= 27 September 2018 |publisher=ESRC|author=Alex Hulkes}}</ref>\n\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Highest total research income for universities (out of 161 British universities, year 2018/19)\n|-  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:center;\"\n|  style=\"width:50px; \"| '''Rank'''<ref name=thefindat>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/sites/default/files/breaking_news_files/university-financial-health-check-2016-uk-institutions-finances-2014-2015.pdf|accessdate=23 May 2017|work=Times Higher Education|date=2 June 2016|title=University financial health check 2016}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:210px; \"| '''University'''\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| '''Research income (\u00a3m)'''\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| '''Research income as proportion of income (%)'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:50px; \"| 1\n|  style=\"width:210px; \"| [[University of Oxford]]\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 624.8<ref name=Oxon1819>{{cite web|url=https://www.ox.ac.uk/sites/files/oxford/field/field_document/Oxford%20University%2C%20Financial%20Statement%202018-19_0.pdf|title=Financial Statements 2018/19|publisher=University of Oxford |accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 25.5\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:50px; \"| 2\n|  style=\"width:210px; \"| [[University of Cambridge]]\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 592.4<ref name=Cabtab1819>{{cite web | url = https://www.cam.ac.uk/system/files/reports_and_financial_statements_2019_final.pdf| title = Reports and Financial Statements for the year ended 31 July 2019 | accessdate = 24 December 2019| publisher = University of Cambridge}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 27.0\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:50px; \"| 3\n|  style=\"width:210px; \"| [[University College London]]\t\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 481.1<ref name=UCL1819>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/finance/sites/finance/files/2019_ucl-annual-report.pdf|title=Annual Report and Financial Statements for the year ended 31 July 2019|publisher=University College London|accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 32.4\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:50px; \"| 4\n|  style=\"width:210px; \"| [[Imperial College London]]\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 368.0<ref name=ImpLond1819>{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/administration-and-support-services/finance/public/Annual-Report-and-Accounts-web-1819.pdf| title=Annual Report and Accounts 2018\u201319 | publisher=Imperial College London | accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 34.3\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:50px; \"| 7\n|  style=\"width:210px; \"| [[King's College London]]  \t\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 194.7<ref name=KCL1819>{{cite web|url=https://www.kcl.ac.uk/aboutkings/orgstructure/ps/finance/statements/2018-19-financial-statements.pdf|title=Financial Statements for the year to 31 July 2019|accessdate=24 December 2019|publisher=King's College London}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 21.6\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:50px; \"| 43\n|  style=\"width:210px; \"| [[London School of Economics]]\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 33.3<ref name=LSE1819>{{cite web|url=https://info.lse.ac.uk/staff/divisions/Finance-Division/assets/annual-accounts/PDF/18-19-LSE-Financial-Statements.pdf|title=Financial Statements for the year to 31 July 2019|accessdate=24 December 2019|publisher=London School of Economics}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 8.3\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|}\n\n==Graduate earning power==\n\nResearch in 2017 by the [[Institute for Fiscal Studies]] also indicates graduates from the LSE, Oxford and Imperial earn, on average, over \u00a340,000 per year 5 years after graduation, making them the highest earners 5 years after graduation amongst British university graduates.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-41693230</ref> Furthermore, the rest of the golden triangle member institutions, along with [[St George's, University of London|St George's (University of London)]], make up the top 7 table of the highest earners.<ref>http://www.dailymail.co.uk/money/news/article-5093461/The-universities-earn-graduates-highest-salaries.html</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n\n{{gallery\n|title=Golden Triangle (Universities)|width=250\n|lines=2\n|File:Cambridge Peterhouse OldCourt.JPG| [[University of Cambridge]]<br>([[Peterhouse]])\n|File:Imperial College Royal School of Mines.jpg|[[Imperial College London]]<br>([[Royal School of Mines]])\n|File:Maughan-library-1.jpg|[[King's College London]]<br>([[Maughan Library]])\n|File:NABuilding.JPG|[[London School of Economics]]<br>(New Academic Building)\n|File:Bridge of Sighs (Oxford).jpg|[[University of Oxford]]<br>([[Bridge of Sighs (Oxford)|The Bridge of Sighs]])\n|File:University College London, by William Wilkins.jpg|[[University College London]]<br>([[UCL Main Building|Wilkins Building]])\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Research-intensive cluster]]\n* [[G5 (universities)|G5]]\n* [[Global Medical Excellence Cluster]]\n* [[Imperial Universities]] (Japan)\n*[[Institutes of National Importance]] (India)\n* [[MedCity (London)]]\n* [[SES-5 (universities)|SES-5]] A formal grouping of universities in the South East of the UK\n* [[Ivy League]] (older private universities in the United States)\n* [[Russell Group]] A formal grouping of research universities in the UK\n* [[SKY (universities)]] (Korea) \n* [[C9 League]]  The Chinese Ministry of Education's formal grouping of elite universities in China\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=THE95>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=94844&sectioncode=26 |title=Oxbridge windfall |work=Times Higher Education |date=4 August 1995|quote=\"A large amount of the cash awarded to humanities postgraduates still goes to the \"Golden Triangle\" of Oxford, Cambridge and London, British Academy figures reveal.\"}}</ref>\n<ref name=Indy12>{{cite news|author=Kershaw, Alison|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/uk-universities-slip-in-rankings-8196772.html|title=UK universities slip in rankings|newspaper=The Independent|date=4 October 2012|quote=\"Rankings editor Phil Baty said: \"Outside the golden triangle of London, Oxford and Cambridge, England's world-class universities face a collapse into global mediocrity.\"}}</ref>\n<ref name=FT15>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/9cae5cd8-1a88-11e5-8201-cbdb03d71480.html|title=Johnson floats \u00a310bn biotech fund for London|author= Andrew Ward|newspaper=Financial Times|date=25 June 2015|quote=\"[[MedCity (London)|MedCity]] was launched last year to increase collaboration between Imperial College, King's College and University College London \u2013 the capital's three main science universities \u2013 and promote the broader 'golden triangle' between London, Cambridge and Oxford to investors.\"}}</ref>\n<ref name=ReLocate15>{{cite web|url=http://www.relocatemagazine.com/news/rmarriage-03-d2-2015-6588-education-uk-confirmed-as-global-education-superpower-in-new-international-university-rankings|title=UK confirmed as 'global education superpower' in international university rankings|author=Rebecca Marriage |work=ReLocate Global|date=11 March 2015|quote=\"The 'golden triangle' of Oxford, Cambridge and London strengthened its grip on UK higher education: As well as Cambridge and Oxford rising closer to the summit, University College London moved up from 25th to 17th, the London School of Economics rose two places to 22nd and King's College London jumped eight places from 43rd to 31st.\"}}</ref>\n<ref name=NewScientist05>{{cite news|author=Mullins, Justin|url= https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg18624962.800-englands-golden-triangle.html|title=England's golden triangle|newspaper=New Scientist|date=23 April 2005|quote=\"Take a look at any of the various league tables ranking universities around the world ... Oxford and Cambridge are in the top handful, while London's University College and Imperial College sit comfortably in the top 25. ... London, Oxford and Cambridge are a 'golden triangle' of academic success.\"}}</ref>\n<ref name=TES15>{{cite journal|last = Wiggins| first = Kaye| title = The World Reputation Rankings: UK's university 'golden triangle' strengthens grip|url = https://www.tes.co.uk/news/school-news/breaking-news/world-reputation-rankings-uks-university-golden-triangle-strengthens|quote=\"The \"golden triangle\" of Oxford, Cambridge and London has strengthened its grip on the UK's higher education system, according to the latest global reputation rankings from